flower
events.description: c.1200, from O.Fr. flor, from L. florem (nom. flos) &amp;#34;flower&amp;#34; (see flora), from PIE base *bhlo- &amp;#34;to blossom, flourish&amp;#34; (cf. M.Ir. blath, Welsh blawd &amp;#34;blossom, flower,&amp;#34; O.E. blowan &amp;#34;to flower, bloom&amp;#34;). Modern spelling is 14c. Ousted O.E. cognate blostm (see blossom). Also used from 13c. in sense of &amp;#34;finest part or product of anything.&amp;#34; The verb is first recorded early 13c. Related: Flowered; flowering. Flower children &amp;#34;gentle hippies&amp;#34; is from 1967.

events.title: car
events.description: c.1300, &amp;#34;wheeled vehicle,&amp;#34; from O.N.Fr. carre, from L. carrum, carrus (pl. carra), originally &amp;#34;two-wheeled Celtic war chariot,&amp;#34; from Gaulish karros (cf. Welsh carr &amp;#34;cart, wagon,&amp;#34; Breton karr &amp;#34;chariot&amp;#34;), from PIE *krsos, from base *kers- &amp;#34;to run.&amp;#34; Extension to &amp;#34;automobile&amp;#34; is 1896. Car bomb first 1972, in reference to Northern Ireland.

events.title: engine
events.description: from O.Fr. engin &amp;#34;skill, cleverness,&amp;#34; also &amp;#34;war machine,&amp;#34; from L. ingenium &amp;#34;inborn qualities, talent,&amp;#34; from in- &amp;#34;in&amp;#34; + gen-, root of gignere &amp;#34;to beget, produce.&amp;#34; At first meaning a trick or device, or any machine (especially military); sense of one that converts energy to mechanical power is 18c., especially of steam engines.

events.title: gun
events.description: mid-14c., gunne &amp;#34;an engine of war that throws rocks, arrows or other missiles,&amp;#34; probably a shortening of woman's name Gunilda, found in M.E. gonnilde &amp;#34;cannon&amp;#34; and in an Anglo-L. reference to a specific gun from a 1330 munitions inventory of Windsor Castle (&amp;#34;...una magna balista de cornu quae Domina Gunilda ...&amp;#34;), from O.N. Gunnhildr, woman's name (from gunnr   hildr, both meaning &amp;#34;war, battle&amp;#34;); the identification of women with powerful weapons is common historically (cf. Big Bertha, Brown Bess, etc.); meaning shifted with technology, from cannons to firearms as they developed 15c. Great guns (cannon, etc.) distinguished from small guns (such as muskets) from c.1400. First applied to pistols and revolvers 1744. Meaning &amp;#34;thief, rascal&amp;#34; is from 1858. The verb meaning &amp;#34;to shoot with a gun&amp;#34; is from 1620s; the sense of &amp;#34;to accelerate an engine&amp;#34; is from 1930. Gun-shy is 1884, originally of sporting dogs. Son of a gun is originally nautical. Gun-metal (commonly an alloy of copper and zinc) used attributively of a dull blue-gray color since 1905.

events.title: labyrinth
events.description: late 14c., from L. labyrinthus, from Gk. labyrinthos &amp;#34;maze, large building with intricate passages,&amp;#34; especially the structure built to hold the Minotaur, from a pre-Gk. language; perhaps related to Lydian labrys &amp;#34;double-edged axe,&amp;#34; symbol of royal power, which fits with the theory that the labyrinth was originally the royal Minoan palace on Crete and meant &amp;#34;palace of the double-axe.&amp;#34; Used in English for &amp;#34;maze&amp;#34; early 15c., and in figurative sense of &amp;#34;confusing state of affairs&amp;#34; (1540s). Related: Labyrinthine.

events.title: Russian forces meet Germans on G. Front
events.description: Starting on 22 August, Samsonov's Russian forces had met the Germans all along his front, and had successfully pushed them back in several places.

events.title: Battle of Orlau-Frankenau
events.description: them again at the minor Battle of Orlau-Frankenau, where the now-entrenched XX stopped the Russian advance

events.title: Germans attack at Usdau
events.description: Ludendorff issued an order to Franois' now-deployed I Corps to initiate the attack on Samsonov's left wing at Usdau on 25 August.

events.title: German I Corps attack Russian left flank
events.description: German I Corps open its attack on the Russian left flank on 25 August, while orders were sent to XVII Corps to move south and meet the Russian right flank as soon as possible

events.title: Russian First Army advances westward
events.description: Russian First Army advances westward, meeting little resistance. The troops that were formerly directly in front of them had moved to the south, facing the Second Army's right flank. There was still time to close the gap between the armies and thereby threaten the German movements, which by this point were being reported back to Russian headquarters

events.title: Samsonov commits suicide
events.description: Rather than report the loss of his army to the Czar, Samsonov committed suicide by shooting himself in the head on 29 August 1914.

events.title: Russia retreats, Germany advances
events.description: The German Eighth Army now faced only the Russian First. In a series of follow-up battles, notably the First Battle of the Masurian Lakes, the First was almost completely destroyed, and turned back over their borders. A Russian Army would not march on German soil again until the end of World War II.

events.title: Battle Ends, Russia has lost 30,000
events.description: By the time the battle ended on 30 August, 95,000 Russians troops were captured, another 30,000 killed or wounded, and only 10,000, mostly from the retreating flanks, managed to escape. The Second Army no longer existed. The Germans suffered fewer than 20,000 casualties and captured over 500 guns. Sixty trains were required to transport captured equipment to Germany.

events.title: Germans Retreat to Orlau-Frankenau Line
events.description: push the German XX Corps back, and the XX retreated to the Orlau-Frankenau line that night
